</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C32365730437FFF0FF2FFD4EFAF973DF" box="[199,1330,691,717]" pageId="5" pageNumber="326" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8B8636F80437FFF0FF2FFD4EFAF973DF" blockId="5.[151,1437,150,1041]" box="[199,1330,691,717]" pageId="5" pageNumber="326">
<emphasis id="B94DEAEA0437FFF0FF2FFD4EFE8373DF" bold="true" box="[199,328,691,717]" pageId="5" pageNumber="326">Etymology</emphasis>
. From the Latin 
<emphasis id="B94DEAEA0437FFF0FDEDFD4EFD8573DE" box="[517,590,691,716]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="326">carina</emphasis>
= keel, and the suffix – 
<emphasis id="B94DEAEA0437FFF0FCBFFD4EFCBD73DF" box="[855,886,691,717]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="326">fer</emphasis>
= carry, referring to the pronotal carina.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
